  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    User guide&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This user guide describes how to create diagrams in the notation Business-SoaML that is described in D5.3. The editor&#xD;
    has been implemented using the Cordys FP1 development platform (which is a Cordys BOP platform with development&#xD;
    functionalities).&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Creating a Business-SoaML diagram&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    To create a Business-SoaML diagram, the user needs to create a New Cordys Document in the project (right click and&#xD;
    select New -&amp;gt; Other) and select the appropriate type of document, i.e. “Business-SoaML diagram”. Figure 4 shows a&#xD;
    corresponding screenshot: on top the Application Palette list the various applications available for the developer&#xD;
    (only recent applications are shown). On the left is the Shortcut bar. In the middle, two windows are shown: the one on&#xD;
    the background is the Workspace with a single project, while the window on the foreground is for creating new&#xD;
    documents.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;./resources/serviceml_editor_business_soaml_diagram.png&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; height=&quot;323&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 4: Creating a new Business-SoaML diagram&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Once the Business-SoaML diagram has been created, the Business-SoaML editor appears (see Figure 5). On the left is the&#xD;
    toolbox, with the various Business-SoaML elements that can be added to the diagram (middle). On top is the toolbar with&#xD;
    default functionalities for saving, properties, undo, etc. Adding an element to the diagram can be done in two ways:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Click on the element to choose in the toolbox, then click in the diagram; or&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Move the mouse to an empty area in the diagram, and wait for the tooltip to appear. Then select the appropriate&#xD;
        element (see the figure).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;resources/serviceml_editor_empty_diagram.png&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; height=&quot;341&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 5: Empty Business-SoaML diagram&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4>&#xD;
    Creating a Service Contract&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Creating a Service Contract is done in two steps:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Create an empty Service Contract from the toolbox&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Add the two Roles inside the Service Contract, name the two roles.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Draw a connector between the two Roles: this is done in two ways: &#xD;
        &lt;ul>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Select a Role, then click on the “Add Connector” button next to the Role (see Figure 6) and click on the&#xD;
                other Role to connect to.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
            &lt;li>&#xD;
                Select a Role and hold CTRL, then click on the other Role to connect to.&#xD;
            &lt;/li>&#xD;
        &lt;/ul>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;resources/serviceml_editor_adding_connector.png&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; height=&quot;341&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 6: Adding a connector&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Figure 7 shows a completed Simple ServiceContract.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &amp;nbsp; &lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;resources/serviceml_editor_simple_servicecontract.png&quot; width=&quot;600&quot; height=&quot;341&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 7: Service Contract with two roles&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
